Starbucks Capstone Challenge¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains simulated data that mimics customer behavior on the Starbucks rewards mobile app. Once every few days, Starbucks sends out an offer to users of the mobile app. An offer can be merely an advertisement for a drink or an actual offer such as a discount or BOGO (buy one get one free). Some users might not receive any offer during certain weeks.

Not all users receive the same offer, and that is the challenge to solve with this data set.

Your task is to combine transaction, demographic and offer data to determine which demographic groups respond best to which offer type. This data set is a simplified version of the real Starbucks app because the underlying simulator only has one product whereas Starbucks actually sells dozens of products.

Every offer has a validity period before the offer expires. As an example, a BOGO offer might be valid for only 5 days. You'll see in the data set that informational offers have a validity period even though these ads are merely providing information about a product; for example, if an informational offer has 7 days of validity, you can assume the customer is feeling the influence of the offer for 7 days after receiving the advertisement.

You'll be given transactional data showing user purchases made on the app including the timestamp of purchase and the amount of money spent on a purchase. This transactional data also has a record for each offer that a user receives as well as a record for when a user actually views the offer. There are also records for when a user completes an offer.

Keep in mind as well that someone using the app might make a purchase through the app without having received an offer or seen an offer.

Example¶

To give an example, a user could receive a discount offer buy 10 dollars get 2 off on Monday. The offer is valid for 10 days from receipt. If the customer accumulates at least 10 dollars in purchases during the validity period, the customer completes the offer.

However, there are a few things to watch out for in this data set. Customers do not opt into the offers that they receive; in other words, a user can receive an offer, never actually view the offer, and still complete the offer. For example, a user might receive the "buy 10 dollars get 2 dollars off offer", but the user never opens the offer during the 10 day validity period. The customer spends 15 dollars during those ten days. There will be an offer completion record in the data set; however, the customer was not influenced by the offer because the customer never viewed the offer.

Cleaning¶

This makes data cleaning especially important and tricky.

You'll also want to take into account that some demographic groups will make purchases even if they don't receive an offer. From a business perspective, if a customer is going to make a 10 dollar purchase without an offer anyway, you wouldn't want to send a buy 10 dollars get 2 dollars off offer. You'll want to try to assess what a certain demographic group will buy when not receiving any offers.

Final Advice¶

Because this is a capstone project, you are free to analyze the data any way you see fit. For example, you could build a machine learning model that predicts how much someone will spend based on demographics and offer type. Or you could build a model that predicts whether or not someone will respond to an offer. Or, you don't need to build a machine learning model at all. You could develop a set of heuristics that determine what offer you should send to each customer (i.e., 75 percent of women customers who were 35 years old responded to offer A vs 40 percent from the same demographic to offer B, so send offer A).

Data Sets¶

The data is contained in three files:

  • portfolio.json - containing offer ids and meta data about each offer (duration, type, etc.)
  • profile.json - demographic data for each customer
  • transcript.json - records for transactions, offers received, offers viewed, and offers completed

Here is the schema and explanation of each variable in the files:

portfolio.json

  • id (string) - offer id
  • offer_type (string) - type of offer ie BOGO, discount, informational
  • difficulty (int) - minimum required spend to complete an offer
  • reward (int) - reward given for completing an offer
  • duration (int) - time for offer to be open, in days
  • channels (list of strings)

profile.json

  • age (int) - age of the customer
  • became_member_on (int) - date when customer created an app account
  • gender (str) - gender of the customer (note some entries contain 'O' for other rather than M or F)
  • id (str) - customer id
  • income (float) - customer's income

transcript.json

  • event (str) - record description (ie transaction, offer received, offer viewed, etc.)
  • person (str) - customer id
  • time (int) - time in hours since start of test. The data begins at time t=0
  • value - (dict of strings) - either an offer id or transaction amount depending on the record

Data Wrangling¶

Assess¶

portfolio

  • channels should be split into 4 columns 'web', 'email', 'mobile', 'social'
  • offer_type should be encoded with one-hot;
  • id is too complex, should be reencodedand change the name to 'promotion_id'

profile

  • gender has nan values
  • age has nan values(118)
  • became_member_on is date, the data format is not right
  • income has nan values
  • id is too complex, should be reencodedand change the name to 'customer_id'

transcript

  • person and offer_id should be transformed into 'customer_id' and 'promotion_id'
  • Split data stored in dictionary format
  • 'event' contains 4 events, which should be split into 4 tables--'offer received', 'offer viewed', 'transaction', 'offer completed'

Clean¶

In [19]:
# generate new id
def id_generator(data, original_id):
    """Generate a new id dict
    
    INPUT:
    data(dataframe) - a origin data frame
    
    OUTPUT:
    new_id_dict(dict) - new id dict
    """

    coded_dict = {}
    counter = 1
    
    for val in data[original_id]:
        if val not in coded_dict:
            coded_dict[val] = counter
            counter += 1
    
    return coded_dict

engine = create_engine('sqlite:///Starbucks.db')

conn = sqlite3.connect('Starbucks.db')
cur = conn.cursor()

cur.execute("DROP TABLE IF EXISTS portfolio")
portfolio.to_sql('portfolio', engine, index=False)

cur.execute("DROP TABLE IF EXISTS profile")
profile.to_sql('profile', engine, index=False)

cur.execute("DROP TABLE IF EXISTS offer_received")
df_received.to_sql('offer_received', engine, index=False)

cur.execute("DROP TABLE IF EXISTS offer_viewed")
df_viewed.to_sql('offer_viewed', engine, index=False)

cur.execute("DROP TABLE IF EXISTS offer_transaction")
df_transaction.to_sql('offer_transaction', engine, index=False)

cur.execute("DROP TABLE IF EXISTS offer_completed")
df_completed.to_sql('offer_completed', engine, index=False)

Q3: What is the return rate of consumers? What are the return rates for different push coupons?¶

definition of return rate:
back_rate = the num of users with more than two transactions/the num of total users

In [54]:
def row_number(data, partionby, orderby, ascending=True):
    """ Return the order data of each user's transactions
    INPUT:
    data(dataframe) - the data;
    partionby - divide data into different group based on partionby;
    orderby - sort the values based on orderby;
    ascending - the final data will rank ascending by default;
    
    OUTPUT:
    df_rn - the original dataframe with 1 new column rn
    """
    data_new = data.copy()
    data_new['rn'] = data_new[orderby].groupby(data_new[partionby]).rank(ascending=ascending, method='first')
    
    return data_new
In [55]:
def first_2_transactions(data):
    """ Return the records of the first two transactions of each user
    INPUT
    data(dataframe) - the original data;
    
    OUTPUT:
    df_first_2_transaction(dataframe) - with the first 2 times transaction records
    """
    df_rn = row_number(data, 'customer_id', 'time', True)
    
    df_top1 = df_rn[df_rn['rn']==1]
    df_top1.set_index('customer_id', inplace=True)
    df_top1 = df_top1[['time']]
    df_top1.rename(columns={'time':'first_time'}, inplace=True)

    df_top2 = df_rn[df_rn['rn']==2]
    df_top2.set_index('customer_id', inplace=True)
    df_top2 = df_top2[['time']]
    df_top2.rename(columns={'time':'second_time'}, inplace=True)
    
    df_first_2_transaction = df_top1.join(df_top2, how='outer')
    df_first_2_transaction['duration'] = df_first_2_transaction['second_time'] - df_first_2_transaction['first_time']
    df_first_2_transaction.sort_values('duration', inplace=True)
    return df_first_2_transaction
In [56]:
def display_back_rate(data):
    """Calculate back rate
    INPUT
    data(dataframe) - the original data;
    
    OUTPUT:
    back_rate(percentage) - return rate
    """
    df_total_top2 = first_2_transactions(data)
    come_back_num = df_total_top2['second_time'].notnull().sum()
    total_num = df_total_top2.shape[0]
    back_rate = round(100*come_back_num/total_num, 2)
    return back_rate

def promotion_difference(data, column, val):
    """Calculate back rate, transaction times and mean gmv of didderent promotion.
    INPUT
    data(dataframe) - the original data;
    column(col) - the specific column of the dataframe
    val(value) - the subset of users when 'column=val'
    
    OUTPUT:
    df_result(dataframe) - dataframes with back rate, transaction times and mean gmv of didderent promotion
    """
    df_transaction_temp = data[data[column]==val]
    promotion_list = list(df_received['promotion_id'].drop_duplicates())

    result = []
    for promotion_id in promotion_list:
        df_received_sub = df_received[df_received['promotion_id']==promotion_id]
        customer_list = list(df_received_sub['customer_id'].drop_duplicates())
        df_transaction_sub = df_transaction_temp[df_transaction_temp['customer_id'].isin(customer_list)]
        
        mean_transaction_cnt = df_transaction_sub['customer_id'].value_counts().values.mean()
        back_rate = display_back_rate(df_transaction_sub)
        mean_gmv = display_mean_gmv(df_transaction_sub)
        result.append({
            'column': column,
            'val': val,
            'promotion_id': promotion_id,
            'transaction_cnt': mean_transaction_cnt,
            'back_rate': back_rate,
            'mean_gmv': mean_gmv
        })
    df_result = pd.DataFrame(result, columns=['column', 'val', 'promotion_id', 'transaction_cnt', 'back_rate', 'mean_gmv'])
    return df_result

Summary¶

-Age: With the increasing of age, the return rate of consumers begins to decline, but the consumption quota will increase each time(in addition to the 55 year old data, the missing age was filled with an average of 55 years, which led to this situation), and the consumption quota of single consumption is the highest at the age of 80 or so. There is not much difference in the reflow rate of consumption among different age groups;;

-Gender: male consumers have higher consumption frequency and reflow speed, while female consumers have higher single average consumption;

-Member Duration: the frequency of consumption decreased three times, 250 days, 600 days and 1400 days after becoming a member respectively; the speed of backflow also decreased significantly after becoming a member 1400 days; the average consumption level of members from 750 days to 1400 days was the highest;

-Compared with information, BOGO and discount can improve consumption frequency and reflow speed, but they have no significant effect on the average consumption;

-Discount has more advantages than BOGO in increasing consumption frequency; BOGO has more advantages in promoting consumer return; if the goal of the business is to let more consumers buy, reflecting prosperity, discount is a good overall strategy, but if in the short term, increasing the probability of consumer return, BOGO is a more correct choice;

def remove_outliers(data, column):
    """remove the outliers of column in data
    INPUT
    data(dataframe) - the original data;
    column(col) - the specific column of the dataframe
    
    OUTPUT:
    data_outliers_removed(dataframe) - dataframe without outliers
    """
    # identify outliers
    IQR = data[column].quantile(0.75) - data[column].quantile(0.25)
    outlier_top = data[column].quantile(0.75) + 1.5 * IQR 
    outlier_bottom = data[column].quantile(0.25) - 1.5 * IQR 

    # removed outliers
    data_outliers_removed = data[(data[column] < outlier_top) & (data[column] > outlier_bottom) ]
    return data_outliers_removed

Measurement¶

In [168]:
#measurement
def rmse(y, yhat):
    """This function can be used to create the RMPE.

    INPUT:
        y: the true values. 
        yhat: the predicted values. 
    OUTPUT:
        the value of rmpe
    """   
    return np.sqrt(np.mean((yhat-y) ** 2))

def rmspe(y, yhat):
    """This function can be used to create the RMSPE.

    INPUT:
        y: the true values. 
        yhat: the predicted values. 
    OUTPUT:
        the value of rmspe
    """   
    return np.sqrt(np.mean((yhat/y-1) ** 2))

def rmspe_xg(yhat, y):
    """This function can be used to create the RMSPE with xgboost model.

    INPUT:
        y: the result of xgboost model. 
        yhat: the predicted values. 
    OUTPUT:
        the value of rmspe
    """       
    y = np.expm1(y.get_label())
    yhat = np.expm1(yhat)
    return "rmspe", rmspe(y, yhat)
